In the first half of the year, I worked mainly on the Global Reconciliation project, supporting Spark reconciliation debugging, data validation, break analysis, and production support activities.

For Risk & Control, I focused on making sure reconciliation results were reviewed carefully before treating them as actual business breaks. I checked record counts, input files, schema mapping, pass keys, duplicate handling, and output breaks during issue analysis. This helped me understand whether a break was caused by real data differences or by configuration, parsing, or job-related issues.

For the Technology Manifesto / Client & Franchise goal, I worked on improving the quality of my technical analysis. One example was debugging a same-file reconciliation issue where the files were expected to match, but the job still produced a high number of breaks. I reviewed the Spark logs and learned that issues such as incorrect input parsing, missing schema columns, invalid pass keys, and duplicate handling can impact the final reconciliation output.

I also supported production-related troubleshooting by reviewing logs, checking configuration files, validating file paths, and following up on issues. This helped me become more comfortable with the Global Reconciliation flow and the way Spark jobs generate reconciliation results.

My main accomplishments were improving my understanding of the reconciliation process, becoming better at Spark job debugging, supporting validation activities, and learning how to connect technical issues with reconciliation outcomes.

One challenge was that some issues required deeper analysis because the final break count did not always show the real root cause. I am continuing to improve my ability to identify problems earlier and communicate risks or blockers more clearly.

For the rest of the year, I want to take more end-to-end ownership of Global Reconciliation work, improve my debugging speed, strengthen my data validation approach, and continue building deeper knowledge of the platform and business rules.
